%[text] %[text:anchor:T_DBB4BEDF] # Compress Deep Learning Models, Generate Code, and Profile Performance
%[text] This exercise requires **Deep Learning Toolbox Model Quantization Library, MATLAB Coder Interface for Deep Learning,** and a **GNU C++ Compiler, such as** **`g++`****\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*\*.** Check `mex -setup C++.`
%[text] Exercise 3 covers a three-part workflow to optimize deep learning models for deployment. Initially, you will apply the projection technique to **compress** a deep learning model, reducing its size while aiming to retain its accuracy. Following the compression, you will use Simulink to **generate C code** for both the original and compressed models. The final part involves **performance profiling**, where you will compare the execution time of the generated code for both models, providing insights into the efficiency improvements achieved through model compression. This exercise is designed to equip you with practical skills in model optimization, code generation, and performance analysis, essential for deploying efficient deep learning models in real-world applications.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%%
clear
proj = currentProject;
%[text] ## Open the instructions in a browser (Optional) 
%[text] We have provided an option for you to have a separate window with the instructions for this exercise for a smoother experience.
open("Exercise_3.html");
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_40922387] ## Load Previously Trained LSTM Network
origFileName = 'trainedNetwork.mat';
load(origFileName);
trainedNetwork.Layers %[output:20eb7a5f]
analyzeNetwork(trainedNetwork)
%[text] Note that the original LSTM network has 4.9k learnables. By default, in MATLAB, DL network learnables are stored in single-precision, floating-point format (fp32). At 4 bytes (32 bits) per learnable, this translates to a total learnables size of **~19.6 KB**. 
%[text] ![](text:image:92d0)
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_23E8EF99] ## Data Preparation
dataFolder = helper.getDataFolder;
trainingFile = fullfile(dataFolder,"Train", ...
    "TRAIN_LGHG2@n10degC_to_25degC_Norm_5Inputs.mat");
[predictors,response] = helper.loadData(trainingFile);

XTrain = predictors(1:10000,:);
YTrain = response(1:10000,:);
XVal = predictors(10001:50:20000,:);
YVal = response(10001:50:20000,:);

testFile = fullfile(dataFolder,"Test","01_TEST_LGHG2@n10degC_Norm_(05_Inputs).mat"); %[control:dropdown:4a1e]{"position":[39,83]}
S = load(testFile);
XTest = S.X';
YTest = S.Y;
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_E8868907] ## Model Compression - Projection
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_D537DD74] ### Understand network compression with projection
%[text] To compress a neural network, MATLAB uses a technique that involves projecting the network's layers into a smaller parameter subspace, thereby reducing the memory footprint of the model. This is done by performing principal component analysis (PCA) on the layer activations using a data set representative of the training data and applying linear projections on the layer learnable parameters. Forward passes of a projected deep neural network are typically faster when you deploy the network to embedded hardware using library-free C/C++ code generation.To learn more about the algorithm based on PCA underlying network projection, refer to [this page](https://www.mathworks.com/company/newsletters/articles/compressing-neural-networks-using-network-projection.html).
%[text] As of R2026a, the following network layers support compression with projection:
%[text] - [`convolution1dLayer`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.convolution1dlayer.html)
%[text] - [`convolution2dLayer`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.convolution2dlayer.html)
%[text] - [`fullyConnectedLayer`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.fullyconnectedlayer.html)
%[text] - [`lstmLayer`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.lstmlayer.html)
%[text] - [`gruLayer`](https://www.mathworks.com/help/deeplearning/ref/nnet.cnn.layer.grulayer.html) \
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_00EE0270] ### Explore Compression Levels
%[text] A trade-off exists between the amount of compression we apply to the network and its accuracy. In general, reducing the number of learnable parameters in a pretrained network will reduce its accuracy. Let's experiment by compressing the network with projection by a range of increasing amounts. To do this, let's iterate over 20 values of the `ExplainedVarianceGoal` in put argument to the `compressNetworkUsingProjection` function and plot the results. Then, we can decide on a worthwhile trade-off point between network size and accuracy.
%[text] The explained variance of a network details how well the space of network activations can capture the underlying features of the data. To explore different amounts of compression, you can iterate over different values of the ExplainedVarianceGoal option of the compressNetworkUsingProjection function and compare the results.
npca = neuronPCA(trainedNetwork, XTrain); % Create Neuron Principal Component Analysis (PCA) object %[output:0cbba751]
numValues = 20;
explainedVarGoal = 1 - logspace(-3,0,numValues);
explainedVariance = zeros(1,numValues);
learnablesReduction = zeros(1,numValues);
accuracy = zeros(1,numValues);



for i = 1:numel(explainedVarGoal)
    varianceGoal = explainedVarGoal(i);

    [dlnetProjected,info] = compressNetworkUsingProjection(trainedNetwork, npca, ...
        ExplainedVarianceGoal=varianceGoal, ...
        VerbosityLevel="off");

    explainedVariance(i) = info.ExplainedVariance;
    learnablesReduction(i) = info.LearnablesReduction;
    
    YPredProjected = predict(dlnetProjected, dlarray(XVal',"CT"));
    YPredProjected = extractdata(YPredProjected(:));
    accuracy(i) = sqrt(mean((YVal - YPredProjected).^2));
end
%%
%[text] Visualize the effect of the different settings of the explained variance goal.
figure %[output:2e749028]
tiledlayout("flow") %[output:2e749028]
nexttile %[output:2e749028]
plot(learnablesReduction,accuracy,'+-') %[output:2e749028]
xlabel("Learnables Reduction") %[output:2e749028]
ylabel("RMSE") %[output:2e749028]
title("Effect of Explained Variance Goal") %[output:2e749028]

nexttile %[output:2e749028]
plot(learnablesReduction,explainedVariance,'+-') %[output:2e749028]
hold on %[output:2e749028]
line([max(learnablesReduction),min(learnablesReduction)],[0.95,0.95],"Color","red","LineStyle","--") %[output:2e749028]
ylim([0 inf]) %[output:2e749028]
ylabel("Explained Variance") %[output:2e749028]
xlabel("Learnables Reduction") %[output:2e749028]
%[text] The graph shows that an increase in learnable reduction has a corresponding increase in RMSE (decrease in accuracy). A learnable reduction value of around 83\*\*%\*\* shows a good compromise between explained variance and RMSE. 
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7BE1822E] ### Compress stacked-LSTM via Projection of Layers
%[text] A learnable reduction goal can be a representative parameter to choose as trade off of accuracy and magnitude of compression. Unpack projected layer is required for embedded code generation. In this case, we can start with an aggressive strategy of 95%.
dlnetProjected = compressNetworkUsingProjection(trainedNetwork, npca, LearnablesReductionGoal = 0.95,UnpackProjectedLayers = 1); % project network with 95% learnables reduction goal %[output:8eb6fc3e]
analyzeNetwork(dlnetProjected)
%[text] The new, projected network has 454 learnables. Still stored in `fp32`, the size now amounts to **~1.8 KB**. The prediction accuracy dropped from 0.976 to 0.839 as the cost for network compression. Next let's try to recover some lost accuracy.
%[text] ![](text:image:0a90)
%[text] 
YPredTrained = predict(trainedNetwork, XTest);
RMSETrainedNN = rmse(YTest,YPredTrained);
accuracyTrainedNN  = 1-RMSETrainedNN %[output:50b2dbe4]

YPredProjected = predict(dlnetProjected, XTest);
RMSEProjectedNN = rmse(YTest,YPredProjected);
accuracyProjectedNN  = 1-RMSEProjectedNN  %[output:58dbfe17]
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_FDD8C48A] ### Fine-tune Compressed Stacked-LSTM Network
%[text] Starting with a pretrained network, the projected network equivalent can be directly computed as demonstrated above. Although a high degree of data covariance is retained, the network may need fine-tuning as accuracy can drop following the compression. This could be a result of higher order nonlinear relations between neurons in the network needing to readjust given the linear transformation or a compounding effect if many layers are projected at once. The projected model provides a good initialization for fine-tuning by further retraining. The fine-tune retraining typically takes far fewer epochs for the accuracy to plateau and can largely recover, in many cases, the accuracy of the original network.
doTraining = true; % Set to true if you would like to run fine-tuning, otherwise, the script will load a fine-tuned model from file below
if doTraining   %[output:group:9c8817a4]
    options = trainingOptions("adam", ...
        MaxEpochs = 300,...
        ExecutionEnvironment = "auto", ...
        InitialLearnRate = 1e-2, ...
        LearnRateSchedule = "piecewise",...
        LearnRateDropPeriod = 120,...
        LearnRateDropFactor = 0.1,...
        GradientThreshold = 1,...
        Shuffle = "every-epoch",...
        Verbose = false,...
        ValidationFrequency = 10, ...
        MiniBatchSize = 32, ...
        Plots = "training-progress", ...
        ValidationData = {XVal,YVal});
    
    dlnetFineTuned = trainnet(XTrain,YTrain,dlnetProjected,"mse",options); %[output:724cc8e7]
else
    projectedModelName="dlnetFineTuned.mat";
    load(projectedModelName);
end %[output:group:9c8817a4]
YPredFineTuned = predict(dlnetFineTuned, XTest);
[RMSEFineTunedNN,residualsFineTunedNN] = rmse(YTest,YPredFineTuned);
accuracyFineTuned = 1 - RMSEFineTunedNN %[output:12051ed4]
figure %[output:0bae95c8]
histogram(residualsFineTunedNN); %[output:0bae95c8]
title("Residuals","RMSE: " + RMSEFineTunedNN) %[output:0bae95c8]
ylabel("Sample Count") %[output:0bae95c8]
xlabel("Y-Y_{pred}") %[output:0bae95c8]
%[text] Save the fine-tuned projected model for simulation and code generation. 
save(fullfile(helper.getCurrPartFolder("P3"), "dlnetFineTuned.mat"), "dlnetFineTuned");
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_6E911296] ## Generate Code from Deep Learning Models
%[text] Open the model:
open_system("SOC_model_Code_Gen");
%[text] To generate code from the **AI subsystem** and inspect the **Static Code Metrics** Report:
%[text] - Open **Embedded Coder** app from the APPS Gallery.
%[text] - Click **Build** button from the C CODE tab. \
%[text] <u>Optional</u>: here are the configuration steps that have been set up for you for your reference. These configurations have been saved with the model.
%[text] 1. Click into the **AI** **subsystem** and apply the same settings for both LSTM and LSTM Projected subsystems. On the **Subsystem Block** pane, under **Component**, click **Atomic Subsystem**. Right-click the subsystem, and select **Block Parameters** **(subsystem)**. In the **Code Generation** tab, set **Function Packaging** to **Nonreusable function**.
%[text] 2. Open the Configuration Parameters dialog box. In the Simulink Editor, on the **Modeling** tab, click **Model Settings**.
%[text] 3. On the **Code Generation** pane, under **Target selection**, specify the system target file as `ert.tlc`.
%[text] 4. Under **Build process**, uncheck **Generate code only**
%[text] 5. On the **Code Generation** \> **Optimization** pane, set **Leverage target hardware instruction set extensions** to **None** \
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_46F67580] ## Inspect Generated Code
%[text] Click "Open Report" on the "C Code" tab on the Simulink Toolstrip.
%[text] ![](text:image:8a21)
%[text] After the **Code Generation Report** window opens, in the "Code" section on the left-hand side panel, click through the "Model files" to inspect the content of the code.
%[text] ![](text:image:64f8)
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_7BC877CC] ## Measure Code Execution Time
%[text] Run the model in SIL mode and collect profiling information. First, let us enable "Measure task execution time" in the Model Configuration Parameters (Ctrl + E). Make sure "Enable portable word sizes" is checked.
%[text] ![](text:image:2b6b)
%[text] Then, On the **Apps** tab, in the **Code Verification, Validation, and Test** group, open the **SIL/PIL Manager** app.
%[text] On the **SIL/PIL** tab, ensure that the mode is set to "SIL/PIL Only". Make sure **SIL/PIL Mode** option under the **Prepare** section is set to `Software-in-the-loop (SIL)`.
%[text] Set Stop Time to **100** to speed up the profiling process while running inference on a reasonably large input data set\*\*.\*\* On the **SIL/PIL** tab, click **Run Verification** to run the simulation and log profiling metrics.
%[text] ![](text:image:45a3)
%[text] After the SIL verification is complete, in the **Results** section of the **SIL/PIL** tab, click the triangle to expand on the list options. Select **Code Profile Analyzer** in the dropdown list.
%[text] ![](text:image:2bea)
%[text] In the **Code Profile Analyzer** window, under the **Analysis** section, select **Function Execution.**
%[text] Change **Time unit** to **Microseconds (us)** and observe the **Average Execution Time** of different subsystems (MLP, LSTM, Projected LSTM).
%[text] ![](text:image:65af)
%[text] <u>Notes on interpreting the results</u>:
%[text] You might see functions of the same name showing up multiple times in the "Section" column. In this example, "MLP", "LSTM", and "Projected LSTM" appear three times. This is because there are three separate functions being called on a single component:
%[text] - **Initialize** - called exactly once for initializing the simulation
%[text] - **Step** - called at each time step as simulation continues to run
%[text] - **Terminate** - called exactly once for terminating the simulation \
%[text] **Code Profile Analyzer** shows the execution times of all three functions of a component. **Initialize** and **Terminate** functions have small execution costs, whereas the execution time for **Step** function is much more significant - this is what we focus on for the analysis, as indicated in the blue box.
%%
%[text] <u>Optional</u>: here are the configuration steps that have been set up for you for your reference. These configurations have been saved with the model.
%[text] To configure code execution profiling for SIL mode simulation:
%[text] 1. Open the **Configuration Parameters** dialog box. In the Simulink Editor, on the **Modeling** tab, click **Model Settings**.
%[text] 2. In the **Code Generation** \> **Verification** pane, under **Code execution time profiling**, select the **Measure task execution time** check box.
%[text] 3. For the function execution times, select `Coarse (referenced models and subsystems only)` from the **Measure function execution times** list. This option allows you to analyze generated function code for the main model components.
%[text] 4. In the **Workspace variable** field, specify the variable name as `executionProfile`. When you run the simulation, the software generates a variable with this name in the MATLAB base workspace. The variable, an object of type `coder.profile.ExecutionTime`, contains the execution time measurements. In the **Data Import/Export** pane, under **Save to workspace or file**, select the **Single simulation output** check box and specify the variable name as `out`. The software also creates the `executionProfile` variable in the `out` variable (`Simulink.SimulationOutput` object).
%[text] 5. In the **Code Generation** \> **Verification** pane, under **Code execution time profiling**, select `Metrics only` from the [Save options](https://www.mathworks.com/help/ecoder/ref/saveoptions.html) (Embedded Coder) list. This option helps reduce bandwidth usage for the communication channel between Simulink and the target application.
%[text] 6. In the **Hardware Implementation** pane, select the type of hardware to use to implement the system represented by the model. This example uses the default value `x86–64 (Linux64)`.
%[text] 7. Click **OK**. \
%[text] The prediction implementations that use MATLAB Function blocks require support for variable signals to be enabled for code generation. To enable code generation support:
%[text] 1. Open the Configuration Parameters dialog box. In the Simulink Editor, on the **Modeling** tab, click **Model Settings**.
%[text] 2. In the **Code Generation** \> **Interface** pane, under **Software environment**, select the **variable-size signals** check box. \
%%
%[text] %[text:anchor:H_F04983F6] Root mean squared error helper function
function [rmseValue,residuals] = rmse(y,t)
    residuals = y(:)-t(:);
    rmseValue = sqrt(mean(residuals.^2));
end
%%
